Basic regression
The most basic form of linear regression states the following constraint:
\[
E Y |X = \beta^T \mathbf{x} = \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \ldots \beta_p x_p
\]
Often regression is motivated as ‚Äúprediction‚Äù. Given a set of predictors \(x_1, \ldots x_p\), what is our prediction, \(\hat{y}\)? If our prediction \(p(y|\mathbf{x})\), is centered on a mean (as above), then our prediction will be poor when \(p(y|\mathbf{x})\) exhibits

skewness




xpower = function(x, p) {
  if(p == 0) {
    return(log(x))
  }
  else {
  return((x^p - 1) / p)
  }
  # return(x^p)
}

df = data.frame(x = seq(0.1, 4, by = 0.01))

p = df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = x)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(y = "")

powList = -1:4
cols = viridis::turbo(n=length(powList))

for (i in seq_along(powList)) {
  p = p + 
  stat_function(fun = xpower, args = list(p = powList[i]), color = cols[i])
}

p

